@inproceedings{,
   abstract = {Fricke gel dosimeters (FXGs) have been the preferred dosimeters because of its ease in preparation and water and tissue equivalency. Visible changes happen three dimensionally in the dosimeter as the ferrous (Fe2+) ions change into ferric (Fe3+) ions upon irradiation and the measure of this change can be correlated to the dose absorbed. Nanoparticles are promising entities that can improve the sensitivity of the gel dosimeter. Cerium Oxide nanoparticle was investigated for possible enhancement of absorbed dose in the FXG. Various concentrations of the nanoparticle based gel dosimeters were prepared and irradiated for a clinical dose range of 0-3 Gy in a telegamma unit. The optimal concentration of 0.1 mM nanoparticle incorporated in the FXG enhances the radiation sensitivity of the unmodified FXG taken as reference without modifying the background absorbance prior to irradiation. The gel recipe consisted of 5% (wt) gelatin, 50 mM Sulphuric acid, 0.05 mM Xylenol Orange, 0.5 mM Ferrous Ammonium Sulphate and 0.1 mM Cerium (IV) Oxide nanoparticle (< 25 nm particle size) and triple distilled water. The FXGs with nanoparticle showed linear dose response in the dose range tested.},
